t6214.text: "This #InternationalColourDay – March 21 is when the #equinox (from the #Latin aequus [“equal”] and nox [“night”]), with its balance of light and darkness, takes place – let us revel in seeing the world in more than just #black and #white." #LanguageMatters

t6215.text: " #ProtoIndoEuropean root bhleg evolved... into #ProtoGermanic blankaz 'bright, shining, blinding, white' > #Frankish blank 'bright, white'... another #PIE root kweit 'to shine' dev'd into ProtoGermanic hweit, then #OldEnglish hwit 'bright, radiant, clear, fair' > #English #white"

t6216.text: "The association of blackness with burnt material is also seen in a completely different family: in the #Australian #Aboriginal #Yandruwandha language, tyimpa means #black and is related to a word meaning 'ashes'."

t6217.text: "In #English, #black comes from #OldEnglish blæc 'absolutely dark, absorbing all light, colour of soot or coal', descending fr #ProtoGermanic blakaz 'burned' (source of other #Germanic words such as... in #Swedish & #Dutch...), from #ProtoIndoEuropean bhleg 'to burn, to gleam'."

t6218.text: "Regardless of culture & lg, though, there is a hierarchy – the majority of cultures recog­nised & named #colours in the same order – wh matches human rxn to diff frequencies in the #visiblespectrum, w/ more salient rxns recognised earlier ... the contrast between dark & light."

t6219.text: "Of the many colour systems, the one that is most widely used – #Pantone – has 1,114 colours. When it comes to basic #colourterms – single-word, high-frequency names – most natural languages have between two and 11: #Alaskan Yup’ik has five, #English 11 and #Italian 12."

t6220.text: Today 21 March is the #northernhemisphere #vernalequinox & also #InternationalColourDay - see my #LanguageMatters column on the #hierarchy of #colourterms in diff languages & the origin of the words #black & #white https://www.scmp.com/magazines/post-magazine/short-reads/article/3001785/origin-words-black-and-white-international … @SCMPNews #OldEnglish #ProtoIndoEuropean
